<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n25106i"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n25" href="#n25106i">N25 (VI.B.15)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n25all.htm#n25106i"> 106(i)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> mickle joy</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Again, at his passing, Arthur says that he is about to go to the splendid elf, Argante (Morgain, or Morgan, la f&eacute;e); &ldquo;she will heal me of all my wounds, and shall make me all hale; and afterwards I shall come to my kingdom and dwell among the Britons with <mark>mickle <font color="green">[great]</font> joy</mark>.&rdquo; Arthur&apos;s byrnie <font color="green">[coat of mail]</font> was made for him by Wygar, &ldquo;the elvish smith&rdquo;; his spear by Griffin, of the city of the wizard Merlin (Kaermerddin); his sword, Caliburn, was wrought with magic craft in Avalon; the Round Table was constructed by a strange carpenter from oversea. Layamon&apos;s account of the Round Table is much fuller than that of Wace, and is evidently based upon popular legends of wizardry. <small> W. Lewis Jones, <a name="WJKA2" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#WJKA2"><cite title="source">King Arthur in History and Legend</cite></a> (1914) 92-3</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c14065g" href="c14all.htm#c14065g">VI.C.14:065(g)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
